{
  "text": "Although 45% of post-craniotomy patients reported no pain in the immediate postoperative period [CITATION_1] , 60-80% of patients reported moderate to severe pain [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . This undertreated pain during intracranial operation is due to fear of causing respiratory depression and masking changes in conscious due to surgical complications by sedative effects of opioids. Regional anesthesia such as wound infiltration or SNB might be a better choice for pain relief. Scalp infiltration by local anesthetics was previously shown to be beneficial for post-operative analgesia in the early post-operative period [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [13] . Three studies of SNB after skin closure resulted in lower pain score and less analgesic requirement [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] .",
